<h1 class="hero-h">How to write discovery call summaries <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">with Claude.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">Discovery call summaries either get skipped (rep moves to next call), or take 30 minutes that the rep does not have. Claude turns a transcript into a structured summary, CRM update, and follow-up email in 5 minutes. Here is the workflow.</p>
</div></div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">The premise</span><h2 class="h2">Why discovery summaries matter and why they get skipped</h2>
    <p class="body">A good discovery summary informs proposal quality, next-call context, and account handoff if anything changes. A bad or missing summary means the rep operates from memory — which decays fast.</p>
    <p class="body">Most reps skip summaries because they take 20-30 minutes manually. Claude does the work in 5 minutes if you brief it correctly.</p>
    </div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">The Claude prompt</span><h2 class="h2">Use this</h2>
    <p class="body"><pre>Here is the transcript of a discovery call I just finished with [PROSPECT] at [COMPANY]: [PASTE TRANSCRIPT]

Produce 3 outputs:

1. CRM update (8-12 bullets):
- Their stated pain points (in their words)
- Current solution and what is wrong with it
- Buying process (who is involved, timeline)
- Specific commitments made by either side
- Next step agreed

2. Follow-up email to the prospect (150 words):
- Open referencing 1-2 specific things they said
- Recap the agreed next step
- Attach the 1 resource I promised
- Close with timing

3. Internal note for my manager (5 bullets):
- Likelihood this deal closes (1-10 with reasoning)
- Biggest risk to the deal
- The 1 specific support I need from leadership
- Coaching point for me on this call (be honest)
- Question I should be asking on the next call</pre></p>
    </div></section>

